  "response": "To define a \"WORKLOAD MATRIX\" for a two-person team in a final year project, you can create a structured approach that outlines responsibilities, tasks, and time allocation. Here's a comprehensive guide:\n\n1. Basic Structure:\n```\nWorkload Matrix Template:\n| Task Category | Team Member 1 | Team Member 2 | Total Effort | Priority |\n```\n\n2. Recommended Columns:\n- Task Category\n- Assigned Team Member\n- Estimated Hours\n- Start Date\n- End Date\n- Priority Level\n- Dependency\n- Status\n\n3. Sample Workload Matrix Example:\n```\n| Task Category | Team Member 1 | Team Member 2 | Total Hours | Priority |\n|--------------|---------------|---------------|-------------|----------|\n| Research     | 40 hours      | 35 hours      | 75 hours    | High     |\n| Design       | 30 hours      | 35 hours      | 65 hours    | High     |\n| Implementation| 60 hours     | 55 hours      | 115 hours   | Critical |\n| Testing      | 25 hours      | 30 hours      | 55 hours    | Medium   |\n| Documentation| 20 hours      | 25 hours      | 45 hours    | Low      |\n```\n\n4. Key Considerations:\n- Balance workload relatively evenly\n- Consider individual strengths\n- Allow flexibility\n- Regular review and adjustment\n\n5. Tracking Tools:\n- Excel spreadsheet\n- Project management software\n- Trello\n- Microsoft Project\n\n6. Additional Recommendations:\n- Weekly progress meetings\n- Clear communication channels\n- Collaborative task management\n- Periodic workload redistribution",
